				<p class="h1">Instant Pot Maple Glazed Pork Loin</p>
				<p class="h3">Ingredients</p>
				<ul class="">
					<li>2.5 lb pork loin NOT pork tenderloin</li>
					<li>4 tablespoons canola oil</li>
                    <li>1/2 cup Maple syrup</li>
                    <li>1.5 tablespoon grainy dijon mustard</li>
                    <li>1.5 tablespoon cider vinegar</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon worcestershire sauce</li>
                    <li>1/2 teaspoon soy sauce</li>
                    <li>1 teaspoon garlic, minced (optional)</li>
                    <li>1 teaspoon minced onion (optional)</li>
                    <li>1/2 cup Beef Buillion</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon corn starch (aprx.)</li>
				</ul>
                <p class="h3">Instructions</p>
                <ol class="">
	                <li>Remove meat from fridge 30 minutes before making recipe to bring meat to room temperature. Pat loin dry with paper towel and season with kosher salt</li>
                    <li>Turn your Instant pot to saute (normal), and add 2 tablespoons canola oil. Once oil begins to shimmer brown loin on all sides, about 4 minutes each. Remove and set aside.</li>
                    <li>Add garlic, onion and remaining oil, saute 30 seconds or until you begin to smell the garlic. Deglaze pot by adding 1/4 cup beef buillion, use a wooden spoon or spatula to dig up all the crispy bits on the bottom of the pot. Add maple syrup, mustard, vinegar, Worcestershire sauce and soy sauce.</li>
                    <li>Put meat on trivet.</li>
                    <li>Turn on manual setting for 12 minutes on high pressure with a natural release for 8 minutes. Remove meat and cut thinly against the grain.</li>
                    <li>Turn Instant Pot back to saute. Add cornstarch to remaining 1/4 cup of stock and mix thoroughly ensuring there are no lumps. Bring to a boil and turn saute to low. Simmer and reduce liquid by half. Serve with pork loin.</li>
                </ol>
